{
  "answer": "**No single English word fully captures *dharma* across these smṛtis, as it denotes cosmic order, obligatory social/ritual roles, moral virtues, legal norms, scriptural authority, and personal conscience—often simultaneously. 'Duty' strains in cosmological contexts (e.g., primordial separation from *adharma*, emphasizing foundational righteousness over personal obligation). 'Law' falters in ethical summaries (stressing virtues like non-violence, beyond statute). 'Virtue' collapses under caste-specific mandates (prescribed occupations as inescapable roles). Translators often retain *dharma* or vary terms painfully.**\n\n**'Duty' misses cosmic order:** In Manu's creation myth, the Self-existent One \"separate[s] Dharma (righteousness) from non-Dharma,\" establishing the moral axis of the universe—not individual tasks.[^1]\n\n**'Law' misses ethical virtues:** Manu's précis of *dharma* for all castes—\"Non-violence, truthfulness, non-stealing, purity, and control of the senses\"—evokes inner qualities, not mere rules.[^2]\n\n**'Virtue' misses obligatory roles:** Yājñavalkya assigns *dharma* as \"sacrificing, studying, and giving\" for Vaiśyas/Kṣatriyas (plus teaching/gifts for Brahmins), rigid functions by birth, not optional excellence.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, [Chapter 1, ¶84ef7f](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-84ef7f).\n\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, [Chapter 10, ¶b48a7b](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/10/translation/#p-b48a7b).\n\n[^3]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, [Chapter 1, ¶ca647c](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-ca647c).",
